Durban - In two separate arrests, five men were arrested for the possession of five unlicensed firearms and ammunition in KwaZulu-Natal over the weekend. Two men were arrested by the Ulundi K9 Unit, Ulundi detectives and Ulundi crime prevention members at Ulundi Plaza on Sunday for the possession of two unlicensed firearms and ammunition. Lieutenant Colonel Thulani Zwane, police spokesperson, said: “The two suspects were searched and were found in possession of two unlicensed firearms and ammunition. It is possible that they were on their way to commit crime. Both suspects were arrested and charged for the possession of unlicensed firearm and ammunition.” Zwane said the men, aged 24 and 39, are expected to appear at the Ulundi Magistrate’s Court on Monday. “The recovered firearms will be sent for ballistic tests to established if they were used in any other crimes in the province,” said Zwane. Earlier, three men believed to be from the KwaMashu Hostel were arrested for the possession of three unlicensed firearms and ammunition. Zwane said they were arrested by after police followed up information about a planned robbery at a business premises in Inanda. The men were stopped before committing the robbery. They are due to appear in the Ntuzuma Magistrate’s Court on Monday. Major General Bheki Langa, KwaZulu-Natal Acting Provincial Commissioner commended the members for the arrest and the recovery of the unlicensed firearms. “Our members are still conducting the Safer Festive Season Operations in the province and we already achieved good successes since the start of Safer Festive Season operations. The police are on the alert and conducting various operations to ensure that criminals are brought to book. Arrested suspects are being profiled and see if they are not linked to any other trio crimes in the province,” said Langa. Daily News